SIMPLE: safety
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Safety
<hw>Safe"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>sauvet⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or
state of being safe; freedom from danger or hazard; exemption from hurt,
injury, or loss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Up led by thee,⟦br⟧
Into the heaven I have presumed,⟦br⟧
An earthly guest . . . With like <qex>safety</qex> guided down,⟦br⟧
Return me to my native element.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Freedom from whatever exposes one to danger or from
liability to cause danger or harm; safeness; hence, the quality of
making safe or secure, or of giving confidence, justifying trust,
insuring against harm or loss, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Would there were any <qex>safety</qex> in thy sex,⟦br⟧
That I might put a thousand sorrows off,⟦br⟧
And credit thy repentance!</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Preservation from escape; close custody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Imprison him, . . . ⟦br⟧
Deliver him to <qex>safety</qex>; and return.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Amer. Football)</fld> <def>the act or result of a
ball-carrier on the offensive team being tackled behind his own goal
line, or the downing of a ball behind the offensive team's own goal line
when it had been carried or propelled behind that goal line by a player
on the offensive team; such a play causes a score of two points to be
awarded to the defensive team; -- it is distinguished from
<contr>touchback</contr>, when the ball is downed behind the goal after
being propelled there or last touched by a player of the defending team.
See <er>Touchdown</er>. Same as <cref>Safety touchdown</cref>,
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Short for <er>Safety bicycle</er>.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>a switch on a firearm that locks the trigger and
prevents the firearm from being discharged unintentionally; -- also
called <altname>safety catch</altname>, <altname>safety lock</altname>,
or <altname>lock</altname>.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Safety bicycle</ent>⟦br⟧
